{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a60193ab-ea12-4d11-b413-3d219f2f7842","content":"Run this:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis uses the `FullyQualifiedName` filter to match any test whose fully qualified name contains `SmsNotificationTests`, which will run both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds` from that class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d462664d-f17b-4d33-a5de-0c42190fb607","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"TUnit uses its own test filter syntax. The way to filter by class in TUnit with `dotnet test` is to use the `--filter` option. TUnit supports the standard MSTest/VSTest filter syntax for class names.\n\nThe filter for a specific class would be:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nOr you can use the class name filter:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nActually, TUnit uses its own test adapter. Let me think about how TUnit handles filtering. TUnit is built on top of the Microsoft.Testing.Platform, not VSTest by default. \n\nSince TUnit projects typically use `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, I can run the tests with `dotnet test` and apply the standard filter expressions. The `--filter` option should work with TUnit's filtering syntax.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"3404:1BDA61:AF4A01:CD7CDC:69F40289"},"id":"e7f8975f-8b39-43a4-bc23-f801ed60aca7","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:32:03.034Z","parentId":"7cf31dbe-abeb-4040-9b06-41aef45ea419"}
